                        <!-- Insert Algorithm / Intuition of Brute Force Apporach Here -->
                        <p><strong>Why Doesn’t Greedy Work?</strong></p>
<p>The greedy method fails because it always takes what looks best right now, but that doesn’t always give the best total result.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Picking the single highest-value item first fills the bag with 60. But picking two smaller items gives a total value of 70, which is better. So greedy is not always correct.</p>

<p><strong>Use Recursion (Choose or Skip)</strong></p>
<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>Problem Setup:</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>We have a list of items with weights and values.</li>
      <li>We need to find the highest total value we can carry without crossing the weight limit.</li>
      <li><strong>Base Case:</strong> If only one item is left, take it if it fits; otherwise, take nothing.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Steps:</strong>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Skip:</strong> Leave the current item and check the best total value from the remaining ones.</li>
      <li><strong>Choose:</strong> Take the current item (only if it fits) and add its value to the best total from the remaining ones.</li>
      <li><strong>Result:</strong> Pick the option that gives the higher total value.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Using Memory to Speed Up</strong></p>
<ol>
  <li>Make a table to store results for different weight limits and items.</li>
  <li>Before solving again, check if the result is already in the table. If yes, use it.</li>
  <li>If not, calculate it, store it in the table, and then return it.</li>
</ol>
