                        <p><strong>Space Optimization Idea</strong></p>
<p>If we look closely, to fill each cell we only need values from the previous row. So, we don’t need to keep the entire table. We can do this using just one row.</p>

<p><strong>Key Relation:</strong></p>
<p>Each cell is found by comparing:</p>
<p><strong>Best without taking the item</strong> vs <strong>Best if we take the item</strong></p>
<p>Since we only use the previous row for this, we can save space.</p>

<p><strong>How We Do It:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Normally, we first fill one row, then use it to fill the next. But we don’t really need two rows.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
  <li>We only need values to the left of the current column, not the ones on the right. (Because when we take an item, we look at a smaller weight value than the current one.)</li>
</ul>
<ul>
  <li>So, we fill the row from right to left. This way, we don’t overwrite values we still need.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
  <li>Since we now fill from the right, and we only need older left-side values, we can reuse the same row by overwriting it with new values. This removes the need for two rows completely.</li>
</ul>
